{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"688ff348-1ccc-48c6-895f-b10e104593c5","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded; it fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer workload packages.\n\nAfter updating:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails, check that your `.csproj` targets a TFM compatible with the new SDK (e.g., `net8.0-ios`) and that the `maui` workload is listed in `dotnet workload list`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cc1ba006-21fa-41b1-b29a-daf09219268e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question I can answer without needing to look at any files.","outputTokens":234,"requestId":"A856:1BCBFD:63D37B:737D36:69FBE20B"},"id":"e8142e80-7eb1-42e4-9674-d37a2d32a022","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:51:30.248Z","parentId":"05f8673c-9efa-435f-84a5-04e7600e5761"}
